Speedup vs threads=1 at the peak (threads 10): q8_0 4.58x prefill, 4.62x
decode; q4_0 4.51x prefill, 4.55x decode. Throughput saturates at threads
9-10 and dips at 11-12, where the caller plus 11 workers oversubscribe the 12
P-cores against the OS and background threads.

Perplexity unchanged across thread counts (wiki.test.raw, 512-token windows):
  q8_0 16 chunks: threads=1 17.763059, threads=12 17.763059
  q4_0 16 chunks: threads=12 20.658812
  q4_0  4 chunks: threads=1 15.032068, threads=12 15.032068
  q8_0  4 chunks: threads=1 13.382441, threads=12 13.382441
The single-thread q4_0 16-chunk run is elided for runtime; the 4-chunk pair
and the bitwise determinism test cover the equality claim.

### ThreadSanitizer

build/tsan preset (-fsanitize=thread, cannot combine with ASan). thread_pool_test
and model_test ran with no data-race reports. model_test drives the auto-threaded
decode_layer and matvec_quant path against the goldens (embedding, attention,
layer output, logits). matvec_determinism_test is elided under TSan for runtime;
model_test covers the same threaded kernels in seconds.

## Phase 6 (k-quant perplexity)

WikiText-2 test, n_ctx 512, non-overlapping windows, oracle pinned to fp32 kv.
q4_k_m is the mixed llama.cpp quant (132 q5_0, 13 q8_0, 12 q4_k, 12 q6_k here).
engine vs llama-perplexity on the same gguf:

  q4_k_m  16 chunks   engine 18.1301   oracle 18.0497   +0.45%
  q4_k_m   4 chunks   engine 13.5675   oracle 13.4804   +0.65%
  q6_k    16 chunks   engine 17.7689   oracle 17.6720   +0.55%
  q6_k     4 chunks   engine 13.3314   oracle 13.2303   +0.76%

all within the 1% weight-quant budget (docs/VERIFICATION.md layer 4).

## Phase 6 (Accelerate prefill)

matmul_accel dequantizes the weight once then issues one cblas_sgemm
(-framework Accelerate, DBINFER_HAVE_ACCELERATE). measured against the scalar
reference matmul (the naive triple loop, not the NEON matvec) on a 512-row
batch, tests/accel_matmul_test. M3 Max, single call, average of 20.

  matmul [m=512 out=512 in=896]   scalar 156.463 ms   accel 0.316 ms   494x

max abs error accel vs scalar 1.5e-5, within the 1e-3 GEMM tolerance. the
wrapper is not wired into forward(): decode still runs one token at a time, so
the default decode path and its perplexity are byte-for-byte unchanged. the
figure sizes the headroom a batched prefill would unlock against the scalar
reference, and is the reason llama-bench's pp512 outruns this engine.
